p":"false","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2015-03-04T00:07:57.524Z","firstPublicationDate":"2015-03-03T16:02:25.482Z","body":"<p><strong>Name: </strong>Russell Tovey.</p> <p><strong>Age:</strong> 33.</p> <p><strong>Appearance: </strong>Unconventionally good-looking. On the pro side: buff. On the con side: ears like wing mirrors.</p> <p><strong>Who is he?</strong> He’s one of “our leading actors”, mostly on television.</p> <p><strong>Which shows might I remember him from? </strong>Sherlock, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/being-human\">Being Human</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/series/looking-episode-by-episode\">Looking</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/nov/22/him-and-her-tv-review\">Him &amp; Her</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/doctor-who\">Doctor Who</a>, Gavin and Stacey, The History Boys (theatre and film), plus a ketchup advert. He’s a gay man who can play both gay and <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2015/09/banished\">straight roles</a>. And, indeed, werewolves. And until Sunday everybody liked him.</p> <p><strong>Why only until Sunday? </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/mar/01/russell-tovey-looking-banished-interview\">Well, he said in the Observer</a> on Sunday that, “I feel like I could have been really effeminate, if I hadn’t gone to the school I went to. Where I felt like I had to toughen up. If I’d have been able to relax, prance around, sing in the street, I might be a different person now. I thank my dad for that, for not allowing me to go down that path. Because it’s probably given me the unique quality that people think I have.”</p> <p><strong>What’s wrong with that?</strong> Well, some people …</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/mar/01/russell-tovey-looking-banished-interview\">Russell Tovey: ‘I was a scared, skinny little rat. Then I hit the gym…’</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>Were these angry people on the internet?</strong> Why yes, as it happens, they were. Anyway, some other gay men especially felt that his comments cast effeminacy in an unduly scornful light. It suggests there’s something wrong with being camp because he’s glad he isn’t.</p> <p><strong>It only just suggests it. </strong>You forget that this is a highly politicised area in the gay world.</p> <p><strong>You forget that some people enjoy being angry.</strong> Maybe. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/mar/03/russell-tovey-sorry-effeminate-actor-drama-school\">Anyway Tovey has apologised now</a>. “I surrender. You got me. I’m sat baffled and saddened that a misfired inarticulate quote of mine has branded me worst gay ever,” <a href=\"https://twitter.com/russelltovey\">he said on Twitter</a>. “I’m proud to be who I am and proud for others. We’re in this together, I want you to know whatever you think I meant, I didn’t.”</p> <p><strong>That’s a logical paradox. </strong>It’s also not really apologising.</p> <p><strong>I’d say that’s appropriate if you’ve not really done anything wrong. </strong>Yes, you would.</p> <p><strong>Do say:</strong> “I’m here! I’m butch! Get used to it!”</p> <p><strong>Don’t say:</strong> “I’m proud to be who I am, although obviously I’d be just as proud if I were somebody else, like you for instance, which admittedly invalidates pride as a concept.”</p>","headline":"Russell Tovey: he may be proud but is the ‘worst gay ever’ actually sorry?","trailText":"The actor is having to backtrack after comments about effeminate men, but something about his Twitter apology fails to fully convince","newspaperPageNumber":"3","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/3/1425397682519/cd1873f6-6bc5-48af-bc23-272b79dde37b-140x84.jpeg","