te":"2015-03-02T15:50:09.520Z","body":"<p><strong>Age:</strong> Five.</p> <p><strong>Appearance:</strong> Everywhere and nowhere.</p> <p><strong>Who, how and the what now? What is </strong><a href=\"http://storyful.com/\" title=\"\"><strong>Storyful</strong></a><strong>? A literacy charity? A movement to bring back public libraries? A children’s literature museum opening soon, ideally near me? </strong>Alas, no. It’s a company that combines digital media and global journalism. No, wait – digital journalism and global media. No, wait – social media and global digital journalism. No – global social media and medium digital globes. No, wait – I think I was right the first time.</p> <p><strong>None of that has helped me. What does it do? </strong>It discovers, verifies and acquires the most valuable content on the social web so that its partners can own breaking news stories with speed and accuracy.</p> <p><strong>Did you get that off Storyful’s own website? </strong>I did, yes.</p> <p><strong>Do you know what it means? </strong>I think it means its global team of journalists source, date and geolocate every piece of content they deliver, and provide direct access to the source.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/jun/25/phonr-hacking-trial-legal-costs-rebekah-brooks\">Phone-hacking trial: total legal costs approach £100m</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>Stop quoting the website and tell me what it actually does. </strong>I think it sifts through all the shite out there and decides what’s slightly less shite and might form the basis of a news report, or possibly what’s totally shite but also total clickbait and might still bring in advertising money/increase traffic/raise your profile as required.</p> <p><strong>Why’s it in the news? </strong>The former chief executive of News International and woman who was acquitted of all charges arising from her years there during which corrupt practices and criminal activities were endemic at the newspaper under her charge, Rebekah Brooks, is about to work there.</p> <p><strong>Why? </strong>Because her former boss/Svengali/ministering angel Rupert Murdoch bought it a few years ago from founder Mark Little and she’s still kicking her innocent heels after the aforementioned phone hacking scandal.</p> <p><strong>I see. It’s a match made in hell. </strong>It’ll probably be in Dublin, actually, as that’s where Storyful is quartered.</p> <p><strong>Ah, Dublin – fair city, where the girls are so pretty, and where endemic, systemic financial and political corruption polluting an entire generation is barely to be found. Sorry, I mean – reported. </strong>Well, quite.</p> <p><strong>Do say: </strong>“Good luck in your new job, Bex! Let me know if you need to pop over for a country supper back in civilisation! LOL! Dave.”</p> <p><strong>Don’t say: </strong>“So – we are in fact all living in a matrix devised by the Chrismorristron computer, yes? Could someone please pull the plug?”</p>","headline":"Storyful: Rebekah Brooks’s new job","trailText":"The former chief executive of News International is taking up a position at the Dublin-based company where she’ll be helping them to geolocate data. Probably","newspaperPageNumber":"3","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"false","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/2/1425308918030/8e641349-f9da-42f6-a6fc-6d749de88604-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"412","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"455649378","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"54f47b8ae4b0bbeb79ca1c2b","internalOctopusCode":"10149695","isPremoderated":"false","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-03-03T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2250617","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-03-05T15:45:00+00:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/mar/02/storyful-rebekah-brooks-new-job-dublin-compan